      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Use Figure 16.12 to explain why Friedel–Crafts alkylations often give polysubstitution but Friedel–Crafts acylations do not.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBbEFWIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--ce85304ec73cbee5d24693737daedc5306bc1761/OChem_16_04_009.jpg\" alt=\"Benzene reacts with methyl chloride in the presence of aluminum trichloride to form mono and para disubstituted products. Benzene reacts with acetyl chloride in the presence of aluminum trichloride to form only one product.\">",
